Project Goal : To understand how different factors affect median house prices in California.¶

To analyze how specific factors influence median house prices in California. By studying the relationship between housing prices and key socioeconomic variables, Through this analysis, we aim to:

Identify the most significant predictor(s) of housing prices. Provide insights that can guide decision-making for stakeholders, such as policymakers or real estate investors. Recommend improvements to predictive modeling by understanding the limitations of linear regression and exploring further refinements.

Overview¶

  1. Median House Value (median_house_value)

    • Definition:: The median price of houses in a given area (in dollars).
    • Range: $14,999 to $500,000 (capped at $500,000).
    • Observation: : The upper cap at $500,000 limits variability, which may impact regression results. Prices tend to increase with higher income levels.

  2. Median Income (median_income)

    • Definition:: The median income of households in a block, measured in tens of thousands of dollars.
    • Range: ~0 to 15.
    • Observation: : Strong positive correlation with median_house_value. Higher income generally leads to higher house prices, making it a strong predictor.

  3. Population (population)

    • Definition:: The total number of residents in a given area.
    • Range: Varies widely, from small clusters to large urban populations (up to ~35,000).
    • Observation: : Weak correlation with house prices. High-population areas do not necessarily have higher house values.

  4. Housing Median Age (housing_median_age)

    • Definition:: The number of occupied housing units in a block.
    • Range: 1 to ~6,000.
    • Observation: : Weak predictor of house prices. The relationship is not clearly linear, suggesting other factors play a stronger role.

Train and Test Split¶

Split the data into training/testing sets. Use the first 80% of the data for training.

In [9]:
# Define the training size (80% of the data)
train_size = int(len(housing_preprocessed) * 0.8)

# Use `.iloc[]` to ensure proper row slicing
train = housing_preprocessed.iloc[:train_size]
test = housing_preprocessed.iloc[train_size:]

# Display the sizes of train and test sets
print(f"Training set size: {len(train)}")
print(f"Testing set size: {len(test)}")

Define,Train and Evalution of model¶

Model 1: Median_income and median_house_value

In [10]:
# Define model for median_income and median_house_value
model_1 = linear_model.LinearRegression()

# Median Income vs. Median House Value
X_train_income = train[["median_income"]]
X_test_income = test[["median_income"]]


# Train the model

model_1.fit(X=X_train_income, y=train[["median_house_value"]])

intercept_1 = model_1.intercept_
slope_1= model_1.coef_

mse_1= mean_squared_error(train[['median_house_value']], model_1.predict(train[['median_income']]))
mae_1= mean_absolute_error(train[['median_house_value']], model_1.predict(train[['median_income']]))

print("The Model_1 for median_income and median_house_value")

# print coefficients
print(f"Intercept: {intercept_1}")
print(f"Coefficients: {slope_1}")


# print the MSE and MAE on the train set
print("Train set")
print(f"Mean squared error: {mean_squared_error(train[['median_house_value']], model_1.predict(train[['median_income']]))}")
print(f"Mean absolute error: {mean_absolute_error(train[['median_house_value']], model_1.predict(train[['median_income']]))}")


# print the MSE and MAE on the test set
print("Test set")
print(f"Mean squared error: {mean_squared_error(test[['median_house_value']], model_1.predict(test[['median_income']]))}")
print(f"Mean absolute error: {mean_absolute_error(test[['median_house_value']], model_1.predict(test[['median_income']]))}")

Summary and Conclusion¶

Among the three models, the regression between Median Income and Median House Value performs the best. It has the lowest Mean Squared Error (MSE) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE), indicating that the model makes relatively accurate predictions. The slope of the regression line suggests a strong positive relationship, where higher incomes are associated with significantly higher house prices. This makes Median Income the most influential predictor of house prices.

The models using Population and Number of Households as predictors perform poorly. Both have high MSE and MAE, and their slopes are very small, indicating weak relationships with house prices. The scatter plots for these features also show no clear linear trends, confirming that these variables are weak predictors.

Key Insights for Modeling¶

  • Median Income is the strongest predictor of house prices.
  • Population and Housing Median Age are weak predictors due to minimal linear relationships with median_house_value.
